{"ts":"2026-07-11T07:03:41Z","op":"query","query":"define rag and explain types of vector search?","answer":"RAG (retrieval-augmented generation) combines external knowledge retrieval with LLM generation. In the wiki, vector search is described as retrieving relevant information by representing queries and documents as vectors and ranking them by similarity rather than exact keyword overlap.  The main vector search types described are: - Dense / semantic search: matches by meaning using dense embeddings, which works well for paraphrases and concept-level similarity. - Sparse / lexical search: matches exact terms using sparse representations and methods such as TF-IDF or BM25-style retrieval, which is useful for identifiers and exact wording. - Hybrid search: combines dense and sparse retrieval to improve recall and robustness. - Multi-vector search: uses more than one vector per document chunk, improving accuracy at higher storage and compute cost.  The wiki also distinguishes two search strategies: exact nearest-neighbor search, which returns the true closest vectors but is expensive at scale, and approximate nearest-neighbor search, which is faster but may trade away some precision.  The wiki pages I opened do not contain a standalone concise definition of RAG beyond its role as a retrieval-plus-generation pattern in production pipelines, so this is the plainest supported summary. Sources: wiki/pages/vector-search-techniques.md, wiki/pages/rag-complete-guide-summary.md, wiki/pages/4-types-of-vector-search-in-rag-summary.md","sources":["wiki/pages/vector-search-techniques.md","wiki/pages/rag-complete-guide-summary.md","wiki/pages/4-types-of-vector-search-in-rag-summary.md"],"index_read_s":80.92539310455322,"page_read_s":5.605257034301758,"synthesis_s":3.0203778743743896,"writeback_s":0,"total_s":89.55102777481079}
{"ts":"2026-07-11T07:08:29Z","op":"query","query":"define rag and explain types of vector search?","answer":"RAG (retrieval-augmented generation) is a retrieve-then-generate pattern: the system first retrieves relevant external information, then uses that context to help the language model produce a grounded answer. The wiki also places vector search as a core retrieval step inside production RAG pipelines.\n\nAccording to the wiki, vector search retrieves information by representing queries and documents as vectors in a high-dimensional space and ranking them by similarity rather than exact keyword overlap. The main types and related retrieval styles described are:\n\n- Dense / semantic search: embeds queries and documents as dense vectors and matches by meaning, often using measures such as cosine similarity. It works well for paraphrases and concept-level similarity, but is weaker for exact identifiers or literal string matching.\n- Sparse / lexical search: uses sparse representations tied to exact terms, including BM25- or TF-IDF-style retrieval. It is useful for product names, codes, and exact wording, but does not provide semantic understanding.\n- Hybrid search: combines dense semantic retrieval with sparse keyword retrieval to improve recall and robustness.\n- Multi-vector search: uses more than one vector per document chunk, such as token-level representations, to improve retrieval accuracy at the cost of more storage and compute.\n\nThe wiki also distinguishes two search strategies:\n\n- Exact nearest-neighbor search: compares against the full dataset to return the true closest vectors, but becomes expensive at scale.\n- Approximate nearest-neighbor search: uses indexing or partitioning to return close-enough matches much faster, trading some precision for speed.\n\nOne caveat from the wiki: one summary page presents the topic as “four types” of vector search, while the more detailed concept page also includes hybrid and multi-vector retrieval as important practical techniques. Sources: wiki/pages/vector-search-techniques.md, wiki/pages/4-types-of-vector-search-in-rag-summary.md, wiki/pages/rag-complete-guide-summary.md\n{"ts":"2026-07-11T07:20:10Z","op":"query","query":"define rag and explain types of vector search?","answer":"RAG (retrieval-augmented generation) is a retrieve-then-generate pattern: the system first retrieves relevant external information, then uses that context to help the language model produce a grounded answer. In the wiki, vector search is described as a core retrieval step in production RAG pipelines. Vector search retrieves relevant information by representing queries and documents as vectors in a high-dimensional space and ranking results by similarity rather than exact keyword overlap.\n\nThe wiki describes these main types or retrieval styles:\n- Dense / semantic search: query and documents are embedded as dense vectors and compared with similarity measures such as cosine similarity. It is good for paraphrases and meaning-based matches, but weaker for exact identifiers or literal keyword matching.\n- Sparse / lexical search: uses sparse representations and term-focused retrieval such as TF-IDF or BM25-style matching. It works well for exact terms, product names, and codes, but does not provide semantic understanding.\n- Hybrid search: combines dense semantic retrieval with sparse keyword retrieval and merges their scores to improve recall and robustness.\n- Multi-vector search: uses more than one vector per document chunk, such as token-level representations, to improve retrieval accuracy at the cost of higher storage and compute.\n\nThe wiki also distinguishes two search strategies used in vector retrieval:\n- Exact nearest-neighbor search: computes distances against the full dataset and returns the true closest vectors, but can be expensive at scale.\n- Approximate nearest-neighbor search: uses indexing or partitioning to return close-enough matches faster, trading some precision for speed.\n\nOne limitation of the current wiki is that it does not contain a standalone formal definition page for RAG; the supported definition is the retrieve-then-generate pattern summarized above. Sources: wiki/pages/vector-search-techniques.md, wiki/pages/4-types-of-vector-search-in-rag-summary.md, wiki/pages/rag-complete-guide-summary.md","sources":["wiki/pages/vector-search-techniques.md","wiki/pages/4-types-of-vector-search-in-rag-summary.md","wiki/pages/rag-complete-guide-summary.md"],"index_read_s":6.125039100646973,"page_read_s":5.391227960586548,"synthesis_s":2.246777057647705,"writeback_s":0,"total_s":13.763044118881226}
